{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ψῡχᾰγωγ-ία</b>, ἡ, <br /> <b>evocation of souls from the nether world,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Philostratus Sophista “Heroicus” 18.3, 12th c.AD: Eustathius Episcopus Thessalonicensis 1614.59. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <i>metaphorically</i>, <b>winning of men's souls, persuasion,</b> whence Rhetoric is called a ψυχαγωγία by [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 261a, compare 271c, “Comica Adespota” 199, 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 1.148S.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also of poetry, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Po.” 2.61, +others\">Refs</a>]:generally, <b>gratification, pastime,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 31.29.5, 1st c.BC: Diodorus Siculus Historicus 1.91, Aristeas 78, LXX.2Mac.2.25, 1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus “Antiquitates Judaicae” 15.7.7, 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Nigr.” 18 \">LXX+2nd c.BC+</a>]; <b>amusement,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Soranus Medicus 1.117 (_plural_)\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; opposed to διδασκαλία, as the aim of a poet, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Eratosthenes Epicus cited in 1st c.BC-1st c.AD: Strabo Geographus 1.1.10: _plural_, μουσικαὶ ψ. 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Mus.” p.86K., compare 2nd c.AD: Aristides Rhetor “Orationes” 29(40).21. \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> (ψυχρός, ψῦχος) <b>cooling treatment</b> in acute fever, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Philumenus Medicus cited in 6th c.AD: Aëtius Medicus 5.78 \">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>] (but, <b>animi oblectamenta procurentur,</b> in Latin version): in heart disease, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th c.AD: Paulus Aegineta Medicus 3.34. \">Refs 7th c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G21363","accentedUnicode":"ψυχαγωγία","shortDef":"animi oblectamenta procurentur","mediumDef":"animi oblectamenta procurentur","stepGloss":"animi oblectamenta procurentur","stepTransliteration":"psuchagōgia","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}